"{\n  \"correct\": \"no\",\n  \"explanation\": \"The np.sinc function does not return 1 at x=0. Instead, it returns 1 at x=0 in the limit as x approaches 0. However, due to floating point precision issues, the actual value returned by np.sinc at x=0 might not be exactly 1. Also, the np.sinc function is defined as sinc(x) = sin(pi*x)/(pi*x) if x != 0, and sinc(0) = 1. So sinc(1) is not equal to zero.\",\n  \"patch\": \"7c7\\n<assert sinc_result[0] == 1, \\\"Results not equal to one\\\"\\n---\\n>assert np.isclose(sinc_result[0], 1), \\\"Results not equal to one\\\"\\n\\n8c8\\n<assert sinc_result[1] == 0, \\\"Results not equal to zero\\\"\\n---\\n>assert np.isclose(sinc_result[1], np.sin(np.pi)/np.pi, atol=1e-8), \\\"Results not equal to expected value\\\"\"\n}"